nd, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"about 1500–":"about 1500–Deceased","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"about 1520","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","about 1500":"about 1500","1549":"1549","Terling, Braintree district, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Braintree, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jackson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish: patronymic from   Jack  . In North America, this surname has absorbed other patronymics beginning with <i>J-</i> in various European languages, in particular those derived from equivalents or short forms and other derivatives of the personal name   Jacob  , e.g. Norwegian   Jacobsen   or   Jakobsen   and, in some cases, Slovenian <b>Jakše</b> (from a derivative of the personal name   Jakob  ). This surname is also very common among African Americans (see also 2 below).","African American: from the personal name <i>Jackson</i> (or <i>Andrew Jackson</i>), adopted in honor of Andrew Jackson, the 7th president of the US; or adoption of the surname in 1 above, in many cases probably for the same reason.","History: This extremely common British name was brought over by numerous different bearers in the 17th and 18th centuries. One forebear was the father and namesake of the seventh US president, Andrew Jackson, who migrated to SC from Carrickfergus in the north of Ireland in 1765. The Confederate General Thomas ‘Stonewall’ Jackson came from VA, where his great-grandfather John, likewise of Scotch–Irish stock, had settled after emigrating to America in 1748."],"variants":[{"name":"Jack","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Jak</i>, <i>Jakke</i>, <i>Jagge</i>, <i>Jake</i>, <i>Jeke</i>, <i>Jegge</i>, a Picard-Flemish denasalized form of Old Picard and Middle Dutch <i>Janke</i>, a pet form of <i>Jan</i> (see   John  ). It was introduced by Flemings and Picards into Norman and Anglo-Norman usage, whence it became a common English and Scottish pet form of <i>John</i>. Although the surname is mainly Scottish in distribution, it also occurs in England, though the more common form there is   Jackson  .","English: occasionally perhaps from a Middle English borrowing of the Old French personal name <i>Jacque(s)</i> (James). However, it is uncertain whether English <i>Jack</i> was ever used as an alternative to <i>James</i>.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Jack</i> (see 1 above) as a surname."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":69,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Jackson was born about 1500, in Essex, England. She had at least 1 son with Jackson."},"et":{"about 1500–":"umbes 1500–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1549":"1549","Terling, Braintree district, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Braintree, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"about 1500–":"noin 1500–Kuollut","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"noin 1520","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","about 1500":"noin 1500","1549":"1549","Terling, Braintree district, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Braintree, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fr":{"about 1500–":"environ 1500–Décédée","1500–Male":"1500–Décédé","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"environ 1520","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","about 1500":"environ 1500","1549":"1549","Terling, Braintree district, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Braintree, Essex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Essex, England":"Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Jackson est née environ 1500, à Essex, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Jackson."},"de":{"about 1500–":"um 1500–Verstorben","1500–Male":"1500–Verstorben","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"um 1520","1520":"1520","1574":"1574","about 1500":"um 1500","1549":"1549","Terling, Braintree district, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Braintree, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","lifeSummary":"Jackson wurde um 1500 in Essex, England geboren. Sie hatte mit Jackson mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1500–":"about 1500–Desede","1500–Male":"1500–Desede","1520–1574":"1520–1574","1500–Female":"1500–Desede","1569":"1569","1558":"1